Session 10 & 11 is one of the MOST SCORING + TRICKIEST sections in CDAC DITISS CCEE, especially because CDAC mixes theory + lab-tool correlation (Snort, OSSEC, Suricata, ELK).

Below are 30 exam-oriented MCQs (10 Basic + 10 Intermediate + 10 Advanced) crafted exactly from Session 10 & 11 + Lab 15 & 16, aligned to CCEE trap patterns.

Network Defense & Countermeasures ‚Äì Session 10 & 11 (IDS / IPS & Threat Hunting)
BASIC MCQs (1‚Äì10)
1. A traditional attack usually originates from:
A. Multiple compromised hosts
B. Single attacker/source
C. Botnet
D. Cloud environment

2. Distributed attacks mainly aim to:
A. Steal credentials
B. Overload resources
C. Encrypt data
D. Modify logs

3. Which intruder type has authorized access?
A. Masquerader
B. Insider
C. Script kiddie
D. External attacker

4. IDS systems are mainly categorized into:
A. Active and Passive
B. Host-based and Network-based
C. Inline and Offline
D. Hardware and Software

5. IPS is BEST described as a:
A. Monitoring system
B. Detection-only system
C. Preventive security control
D. Logging mechanism

6. Defense in Depth means:
A. Single strong firewall
B. Multiple layers of security
C. Only IDS deployment
D. Only IPS deployment

7. Signature-based detection works by:
A. Learning behavior
B. Matching known patterns
C. Blocking unknown traffic
D. Using heuristics

8. Anomaly detection compares traffic against:
A. Signature database
B. Firewall rules
C. Baseline behavior
D. Honeypot data

9. Which tool is a Network-based IDS?
A. OSSEC
B. Snort
C. Wazuh
D. Tripwire

10. Threat hunting is primarily:
A. Reactive
B. Automated blocking
C. Proactive investigation
D. Logging activity

INTERMEDIATE MCQs (11‚Äì20)
11. A botnet-driven attack is an example of:
A. Traditional attack
B. Distributed attack
C. Insider attack
D. Passive attack

12. Which intruder type uses stolen credentials?
A. Insider
B. Masquerader
C. Misfeasor
D. External auditor

13. Host-based IDS (HIDS) typically monitors:
A. Network packets
B. System logs and file integrity
C. Router traffic
D. Firewall rules

14. IPS categories include:
A. Signature, anomaly
B. Network-based, host-based
C. Inline, out-of-band
D. Hardware, software

15. Inline IPS operates by:
A. Copying traffic
B. Blocking traffic in real time
C. Logging packets
D. Forwarding logs

16. IDS analysis scheme involves:
A. Detection, alerting, response
B. Logging only
C. Blocking traffic
D. Encryption

17. Which detection method is BEST for zero-day attacks?
A. Signature-based
B. Rule-based
C. Anomaly-based
D. Static analysis

18. One core principle of IDS is:
A. Eliminate attacks
B. Detect policy violations
C. Encrypt traffic
D. Replace firewall

19. Snort mainly operates as:
A. HIDS
B. NIDS
C. Firewall
D. Proxy

20. Suricata can operate as both:
A. IDS and IPS
B. Firewall and router
C. VPN and IDS
D. Proxy and IDS

ADVANCED MCQs (21‚Äì30)
21. Defense in Depth reduces risk mainly by:
A. Eliminating vulnerabilities
B. Introducing multiple failure points for attackers
C. Increasing bandwidth
D. Centralizing control

22. A false negative in IDS means:
A. Normal traffic flagged
B. Attack missed
C. Attack blocked
D. System crash

23. IDS evasion techniques target weaknesses in:
A. Encryption
B. Detection methodology
C. Hardware speed
D. Load balancing

24. OSSEC is BEST suited for detecting:
A. Network scans
B. Host-level log anomalies
C. DDoS attacks
D. Packet fragmentation

25. Suricata in IPS mode must be deployed:
A. Out-of-band
B. Inline
C. On endpoint
D. In DMZ only

26. An IDS generating too many alerts suffers from:
A. False negatives
B. Alert fatigue
C. Weak encryption
D. Poor routing

27. Threat hunting differs from IDS because it is:
A. Automated
B. Signature-driven
C. Hypothesis-based and proactive
D. Firewall-based

28. ELK stack is mainly used for:
A. Packet filtering
B. Log aggregation and visualization
C. Intrusion blocking
D. Malware removal

29. In ELK, which component parses logs?
A. Elasticsearch
B. Kibana
C. Logstash
D. Beats

30. From CCEE perspective, combining IDS + IPS + Threat Hunting achieves:
A. Absolute security
B. Detection, prevention, and response
C. Encryption only
D. Authentication only

